  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "In accordance with this divine command, they went past the Edomites by the side of their mountains, \"from the way of the Arabah, from Elath (see at ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 14:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") and Eziongeber\" (see at ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 33:35",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), sc., into the steppes of Moab, where they were encamped at that time.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "God commanded them to behave in the same manner towards the Moabites, when they approached their frontier (Deuteronomy 2:9). They were not to touch their land, because the Lord had given Ar to the descendants of Lot for a possession. In Deuteronomy 2:9 the Moabites are mentioned, and in Deuteronomy 2:19 the Amorites also. The Moabites are designated as \"sons of Lot,\" for the same reason for which the Edomites are called \"brethren of Israel\" in Deuteronomy 2:4. The Israelites were to uphold the bond of blood-relationship with these tribes in the most sacred manner. Ar, the capital of Moabitis (see at Numbers 21:15), is used here for the land itself, which was named after the capital, and governed by it.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "God commanded them to behave in the same manner towards the Moabites, when they approached their frontier (",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Deuteronomy 2:9",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "). They were not to touch their land, because the Lord had given Ar to the descendants of Lot for a possession. In ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Deuteronomy 2:9",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " the Moabites are mentioned, and in ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Deuteronomy 2:19",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " the Amorites also. The Moabites are designated as \"sons of Lot,\" for the same reason for which the Edomites are called \"brethren of Israel\" in ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Deuteronomy 2:4",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ". The Israelites were to uphold the bond of blood-relationship with these tribes in the most sacred manner. Ar, the capital of Moabitis (see at ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Numbers 21:15",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "), is used here for the land itself, which was named after the capital, and governed by it.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
